## Why

`glitch ask` today requires knowing the exact pipeline name to get real work done — `--pipeline sync-docs` only works if you remember that pipeline exists. Intent routing closes the gap between natural language ("sync my docs") and the right execution path, making glitch usable as a daily driver without memorising command syntax.

## What Changes

- `glitch ask <prompt>` now routes through an intent classifier before executing: if a known pipeline matches the prompt, it runs that pipeline with the prompt as input
- New pipeline discovery mechanism: scans `~/.config/glitch/pipelines/` and extracts name + description from each YAML
- Add `description` field to the pipeline YAML schema (top-level, optional) for explicit routing hints
- When no pipeline matches, glitch generates one on the fly and asks for confirmation before running
- New flags: `--auto` / `-y` (skip confirmation), `--route=false` (disable routing), `--dry-run` (show what would run without executing)
